    <text id="B0330T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Brackett discusses a school tax law, although the specifics of his letter remain
                    unclear.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Thos. P. Jackson:<lb/>Staunton, <abbr expan="Virginia"
                            >Va.</abbr></name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1868-02-19"><abbr expan="February">Feb.</abbr> 19, 1868</date>
                        <name type="place">Harpers Ferry <abbr expan="West Virginia">W.Va</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>I confess myself to have been very slow, but here is what you want. According to
                    law, the school tax in W. Va. cannot be less than 2 <unclear>mills</unclear> per
                    dollar, or more than 5 <unclear>mills</unclear> per dollar this year it was <del
                        hand="h1"/>
                    <unclear>mills</unclear> per dollar in this county, don't know but in the whole
                    state. We are prospering after a manner, I think I may go up to Staunton to buy
                    a pair or two or horses soon.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very Truly</salute>
                    <signed>N.C. Brackett</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
